A very nice coffee cake and a great way to use up the berries you picked this summer and froze! I omitted the coconut because of fussy family members. Definitely use the pan size stated in the recipe -- I baked at 375 for 45 minutes. A smaller pan will up the baking time. Also, to the cooks who aren't accustomed to cooking with blueberries: Leave your frozen berries frozen, even if they are coated with frost -- the frost won't hurt the end product! If you thaw them they will sink during baking and make a mess of the cake.

Rating: 2
Well, after reading all the reviews, I took the advice and revamped the recipe. It was amazing. First, I added zest of one lemon to topping and didn't use coconut. Then I added zest of one lemon to batter and omitted the cinnamon. Instead of 1 cup milk I used 1/4 c. lemon juice and 3/4 c. milk. It curdled to make buttermilk and made the batter real creamy. Instead of mixing berries into the batter, I placed all the berries on top of the batter then sprinkled the topping over the berries. I baked it in a 10" springform for 1 hr. at 375 deg. In conclusion, I came up with a flavorful, moist cake with all the berries on top encrusted in the yummy topping. I brought it to my bookclub and every last crumb was eaten! In my opinion, blueberries always need some citrus to perk them up. It was great. Try it this way, you'll be the hit of the party.

